  "prompt": "What causes a sonic boom?",
  "response": "A **sonic boom** is a loud, explosive sound caused by an object traveling through the air faster than the speed of sound (approximately 767 mph or 1,235 km/h at sea level). Here\u2019s how it happens:\n\n1. **Supersonic Speed**: When an object (like an aircraft) moves faster than the speed of sound, it compresses the air in front of it, creating pressure waves that travel outward in all directions.\n\n2. **Shock Waves**: As the object moves, these pressure waves cannot move out of the way fast enough and instead pile up, forming a cone-shaped **shock wave** behind the object. This shock wave consists of a sudden, intense increase in air pressure followed by a rapid decrease.\n\n3. **Sound Release**: When this shock wave reaches the ground or an observer, it is experienced as a loud, thunder-like noise called a **sonic boom**. The boom is not just a single event but a continuous sound that occurs along the path of the object as long as it is traveling at supersonic speeds.\n\nThe intensity of the sonic boom depends on factors like the size, shape, and speed of the object, as well as the atmospheric conditions. Sonic booms can be startling and even cause structural vibrations, which is why supersonic flight over populated areas is often restricted.",
